HB 4121-A3
(LC 235)
2/24/26 (DFY/ps)
Requested by Representative EVANS
PROPOSED AMENDMENTS TO
A-ENGROSSED HOUSE BILL 4121
1 On page 1 of the printed A-engrossed bill, delete lines 6 through 19 and
2 delete pages 2 through 17 and insert:
3
4 “STATEWIDE REGIONAL TRAINING OFFICE
5
6 “SECTION 1. (1) The Statewide Regional Training Office is estab-
7 lished within the Department of Public Safety Standards and Training.
8 “(2) The office is under the supervision and control of the Statewide
9 Regional Training Officer, who is responsible for the performance of
10 the duties, functions and powers of the office.
11 “(3) The Director of the Department of Public Safety Standards and
12 Training shall appoint the Statewide Regional Training Officer, who
13 holds office at the pleasure of the director.
14
15 “PROVISIONS RELATED TO THE STATE RESILIENCE OFFICER
16
17 “SECTION 2. (1) The State Resilience Officer shall identify state
18 agencies with responsibility for one or more emergency support func-
19 tions identified by the Federal Emergency Management Agency.
20 “(2) Each state agency identified under subsection (1) of this section
21 shall designate an employee of the state agency as the Emergency

1 Management Responsible Officer. The Emergency Management Re-
2 sponsible Officer shall act as the primary liaison between the state
3 agency and state authorities related to emergency management, in-
4 cluding the Oregon Department of Emergency Management.
5 “SECTION 3. ORS 401.913 is amended to read:
6 “401.913. (1) The office of State Resilience Officer is created in the office
7 of the Governor. The office of State Resilience Officer shall direct, implement
8 and coordinate hazard safety and resilience goal setting and state agency
9 planning and preparation to improve hazard safety and resilience, including
10 but not limited to planning and preparation for safety and resilience during
11 and after earthquake, tsunami, wildfire, flooding and other natural or
12 manmade events.
13 “(2) The State Resilience Officer shall lead statewide efforts to implement
14 the Oregon Resilience Plan, the Natural Hazard Mitigation Plan and other
15 resilience plans adopted by the state.
16 “(3) The State Resilience Officer shall facilitate policy standardi-
17 zation among state agencies, prioritize investments for improving
18 resilience posture and provide regular reports on state agency
19 resilience policy compliance, organizational preparedness, continuity
20 of governance procedures and measures of emergency readiness. Such
21 reports may be made to the Governor, appropriate committees of the
22 Legislative Assembly or relevant public safety advisory boards and
23 commissions.
24 “[(3)] (4) The State Resilience Officer shall lead executive branch agencies
25 in continuity of operations planning and continuity of government planning.
26 “[(4)] (5) The Governor shall appoint an individual to serve as the State
27 Resilience Officer, subject to confirmation by the Senate pursuant to Article
28 III, section 4, of the Oregon Constitution.
29 “[(5)] (6) The legislative branch of government and the judicial branch
30 of government shall each select an individual to monitor the effectiveness
HB 4121-A3 2/24/26
Proposed Amendments to A-Eng. HB 4121 Page 2

1 of hazard safety and resilience planning in their branch.
2
3 “OREGON DISASTER RECOVERY AUTHORITY
4
5 “SECTION 4. (1) The Oregon Disaster Recovery Authority is estab-
6 lished as an advisory group within the Office of the Governor to direct
7 emergency recovery in Oregon. The Governor shall determine the
8 membership of the authority, subject to subsection (2) of this section.
9 “(2) The Governor shall appoint at least eight individuals to serve
10 as members of the authority from among state agency leadership, lo-
11 cal emergency managers and others with expertise in emergency
12 management. The Governor shall seek the advice of the Oregon
13 Homeland Security Council when making appointments to the au-
14 thority. Members of the authority serve at the pleasure of the Gover-
15 nor.
16 “(3) If the Governor declares a state of emergency under ORS
17 401.165, the Governor may activate the authority. The authority re-
18 mains activated until deactivated by order of the Governor. The au-
19 thority may remain activated notwithstanding the termination of a
20 state of emergency.
21 “(4) When activated, the authority shall:
22 “(a) Coordinate initial crisis services;
23 “(b) Coordinate recovery and mitigation efforts throughout this
24 state, using a framework aligned with emergency support functions
25 as defined by the Federal Emergency Management Agency; and
26 “(c) Coordinate the provision of emergency funding and other aid
27 to local governments or private entities.
28 “(5) A majority of the members of the authority constitutes a quo-
29 rum for the transaction of business.
30 “(6) Official action by the authority requires the approval of a ma-
HB 4121-A3 2/24/26
Proposed Amendments to A-Eng. HB 4121 Page 3

1 jority of the members of the authority.
2 “(7) The Governor shall appoint one of the members of the author-
3 ity to serve as chairperson.
4 “(8) The authority shall meet at times and places specified by the
5 call of the Governor or the chairperson. The authority may meet at
6 times when the authority is not activated to maintain readiness in the
7 event of an emergency.
8 “(9) The authority may adopt rules necessary for the operation of
9 the authority.
10 “(10) The Office of the Governor shall provide staff support to the
11 authority.
12 “(11) Members of the authority are not entitled to compensation or
13 reimbursement for expenses and serve as volunteers on the authority.
14 “(12) All agencies of state government, as defined in ORS 174.111,
15 are directed to assist the authority in the performance of the duties
16 of the authority and, to the extent permitted by laws relating to
17 confidentiality, to furnish information and advice the members of the
18 authority consider necessary to perform their duties.
19 “SECTION 5. (1) If the Oregon Disaster Recovery Authority estab-
20 lished under section 4 of this 2026 Act is activated pursuant to a dec-
21 laration of emergency, the Governor may hire additional state agency
22 personnel under this section.
23 “(2) Additional personnel hired under this section:
24 “(a) May be placed at any state agency, including the Office of the
25 Governor;
26 “(b) Must perform duties related to the emergency, which may in-
27 clude taking over duties previously performed by other state agency
28 personnel who have been reassigned to emergency-related tasks; and
29 “(c) Must have their employment terminated no later than the date
30 the authority is deactivated under section 4 of this 2026 Act.
HB 4121-A3 2/24/26
Proposed Amendments to A-Eng. HB 4121 Page 4

1 “(3) Notwithstanding any other law relating to state government
2 employment, additional personnel hired under this section may be re-
3 cruited and selected through any means the Governor deems appro-
4 priate.
5 “(4) The Governor’s hiring authority under this section is subject
6 to the availability of funding. The compensation of additional person-
7 nel hired under this section may be paid from the Oregon Disaster
8 Recovery Authority Fund established under section 6 of this 2026 Act.
9 “SECTION 6. The Oregon Disaster Recovery Authority Fund is es-
10 tablished in the State Treasury, separate and distinct from the General
11 Fund. The Oregon Disaster Recovery Authority Fund consists of
12 moneys appropriated, allocated, deposited or transferred to the fund
13 by the Legislative Assembly or otherwise. Moneys in the fund are
14 continuously appropriated to the Office of the Governor to pay for
15 compensation for personnel hired under section 5 of this 2026 Act.
16
17 “OREGON PREPAREDNESS GRANT ACCOUNT
18
19 “SECTION 7. The Oregon Preparedness Grant Account is estab-
20 lished in the State Treasury, separate and distinct from the General
21 Fund. The Oregon Preparedness Grant Account consists of moneys
22 appropriated, allocated, deposited or transferred to the fund by the
23 Legislative Assembly or otherwise. Moneys in the account are contin-
24 uously appropriated to the Oregon Department of Emergency Man-
25 agement for providing grants to local governments, as defined in ORS
26 174.116, and tribal governments to support their compliance with ORS
27 401.305 (2).
28
29 “ODEM DUTIES
30
HB 4121-A3 2/24/26
Proposed Amendments to A-Eng. HB 4121 Page 5

1 “SECTION 8. ORS 401.114 is amended to read:
2 “401.114. The Oregon Department of Emergency Management shall carry
3 out the following functions:
4 “(1) Coordinate emergency management functions on a regional basis
5 within this state;
6 “(2) Coordinate training related to emergency response on a regional basis
7 within this state; [and]
8 “(3) Develop and carry out emergency preparedness exercises on a state-
9 wide basis[.];
10 “(4) Oversee collaboration, cooperation and coordination between
11 the state and organizations involved in the emergency stockpile plan
12 described in ORS 401.111, the emergency preparedness equipment grant
13 program described in ORS 401.551 and other stockpile or emergency
14 preparedness programs carried out by state agencies;
15 “(5) Take actions as necessary to ensure that supplies, equipment
16 and other materials are appropriately staged in preparation for emer-
17 gencies; and
18 “(6) Develop and maintain an inventory plan for the sustainable
19 procurement, rotation and management of emergency preparedness
20 assets.
21
22 “RESILIENCE HUBS AND NETWORKS
23
24 “SECTION 9. ORS 409.760 is amended to read:
25 “409.760. (1) As used in this section:
26 “(a) ‘Resilience Hub’ means a physical facility that is created, operated,
27 managed or supported by one or more local residents, local governments,
28 tribal governments, public schools, community-based organizations, faith-
29 based organizations, nonprofit organizations, [or] nongovernmental organ-
30 izations or any other groups or entities located in Oregon, and that:
HB 4121-A3 2/24/26
Proposed Amendments to A-Eng. HB 4121 Page 6

1 “(A) Supports the needs of community members or tribal communities,
2 facilitates gathering and communication, distributes resources and otherwise
3 enhances quality of life within a community;
4 “(B) Serves as a central point for gathering, information sharing, and
5 coordination in response to a disruption in the community;
6 “(C) Enhances the ability of a community to respond to and recover from
7 a disruption in a community;
8 “(D) Is positioned, operated and resourced on a day-to-day basis, during
9 a disruption and during recovery, to provide community resources, in-
10 cluding but not limited to food, water, information exchange, electronic
11 charging stations, basic medical supplies and equipment proportionate to the
12 size of the community’s population and needs;
13 “(E) Supports community cache sites and other support for community
14 members who shelter in place;
15 “(F) Can provide child care, training, food distribution and other services
16 that can help a community respond to unmet [social] needs to prepare for,
17 respond to and recover from adverse events, emergencies or disasters;
18 “(G) Can provide, or can be retrofitted to provide, heating, cooling, air
19 filtration and weather protection; and
20 “(H) Accommodates individuals with accessibility needs.
21 “(b) ‘Resilience Network’ means an association of facilities, organizations,
22 resource providers or service providers [outside of a physical Resilience Hub
23 facility that collectively serve the purposes of a Resilience Hub] that collec-
24 tively supports community members to prepare for, adapt to or re-
25 spond to social, emotional and physical disruption generated by
26 ongoing climate change or other causes, and during and after an ad-
27 verse event, emergency or disaster.
28 “(2) The Department of Human Services shall, in consultation with the
29 State Department of Energy and the Oregon Health Authority, provide
30 grants, [support and technical assistance for] equipment, technical assist-
HB 4121-A3 2/24/26
Proposed Amendments to A-Eng. HB 4121 Page 7

1 ance, contracted services and any other type of support to individuals
2 or organizations located in Oregon for creating or sustaining Resilience
3 Hubs and Resilience Networks in Oregon. The Department of Human Ser-
4 vices shall award:
5 “(a) Grants for expenses related to planning and organizing Resilience
6 Hubs and Resilience Networks;
7 “(b) Grants to support and expand development and operation of
8 Resilience Hubs and Resilience Networks to ensure that physical facilities
9 can provide protection from extreme weather, can maintain power and cli-
10 mate during power outages, have auxiliary communications capabilities and
11 are resilient following earthquakes, fires, tornadoes, floods, other extreme
12 weather events and other potential adverse events, emergencies or
13 disasters[, emergencies or incidents]; and
14 “(c) Grants for resources and services needed by communities to otherwise
15 prepare for and respond to adverse events, emergencies or disasters.
16 “(3) Individuals or organizations located in Oregon and serving people
17 in this state may apply for grants by submitting an application that must
18 include:
19 “(a) A description of the purposes for which grant moneys will be ex-
20 pended, including a description of the services to be provided to the
21 community by the Resilience Hub or Resilience Network;
22 “(b) A plan for implementing specific strategies to build resilience in a
23 community;
24 “(c) A description of additional resources available for purposes of the
25 Resilience Hub or Resilience Network;
26 “(d) A description of the project’s ability to serve vulnerable populations
27 and communities traditionally underrepresented in the public process, in-
28 cluding communities of color, communities experiencing lower incomes,
29 tribal communities, rural communities, coastal communities, communities
30 with limited infrastructure, seniors, youth and persons with disabilities; and
HB 4121-A3 2/24/26
Proposed Amendments to A-Eng. HB 4121 Page 8

1 “(e) Any other information required by the department.
2 “(4) The department shall execute grant agreements with grant recipients
3 obligating recipients to use grant moneys for purposes specified in the grant
4 agreements. The department, in consultation with the State Department of
5 Energy and the Oregon Health Authority, shall determine the permissible
6 purposes, applicant eligibility requirements, types of awards for a grant
7 and eligible equipment, technical assistance, services and support un-
8 der this section based on the needs of the Resilience Hub or Resilience
9 Network. The department shall determine the needs of the Resilience Hub
10 or Resilience Network in consultation with the community, including pop-
11 ulations described in subsection (3)(d) of this section, within the locality in
12 which the Resilience Hub or Resilience Network operates.
13 “(5) The Department of Human Services shall adopt rules necessary for
14 the administration of this section, including specifying the form and contents
15 of an application for a grant under this section.
