17 “OVERNIGHT TRAINING ACTIVITIES
18
19 “SECTION 10. Notwithstanding any other provision of state or local
20 law, a facility that is used for emergency preparedness, response or
21 recovery and that receives state funding is authorized to host over-
22 night training activities.
23
24 “COUNTY AUTHORITY TO WAIVE CIVIL PENALTIES
25
26 “SECTION 11. A county governing body may, by order or resol-
27 ution, waive a civil penalty imposed by the Oregon Health Authority
28 or a local health authority under ORS 624.992 if the civil penalty is
29 imposed for a violation that occurred during a state of emergency de-
30 clared under ORS 401.165.
HB 4121-A3 2/24/26
Proposed Amendments to A-Eng. HB 4121 Page 9

1 “DEPARTMENT OF THE STATE FIRE MARSHAL
2
3 “SECTION 12. The Department of the State Fire Marshal shall
4 conduct a study of health coverage disparities between paid and vol-
5 unteer firefighters. The department shall submit a report in the man-
6 ner provided by ORS 192.245, and may include recommendations for
7 legislation, to the interim committees of the Legislative Assembly re-
8 lated to emergency management no later than September 15, 2027.
9 “SECTION 13. Section 12 of this 2026 Act is repealed on January 2,
10 2028.
11
12 “FINGERPRINTING BY ODEM
13
14 “SECTION 14. The Oregon Department of Emergency Management
15 shall require the fingerprints of the following persons for the purpose
16 of requesting a state or nationwide criminal records check under ORS
17 181A.195:
18 “(1) Persons employed or applying for employment by the depart-
19 ment; and
20 “(2) Persons who provide or seek to provide services to the depart-
21 ment as a contractor or subcontractor.
22
23 “PUBLIC AND INDIVIDUAL ASSISTANCE PROGRAMS
24
25 “SECTION 15. Sections 16 to 19 of this 2026 Act are added to and
26 made a part of ORS chapter 401.
27 “SECTION 16. (1) The Oregon Department of Emergency Manage-
28 ment shall establish and administer a state infrastructure emergency
29 recovery grant program, to be known as the Oregon Public Assistance
30 Grant Program, to issue grants to qualified recipients, subject to
HB 4121-A3 2/24/26
Proposed Amendments to A-Eng. HB 4121 Page 10

1 available funding.
2 “(2) Grants under the program must be used to pay for work per-
3 formed before, during or after an emergency to protect public health,
4 safety or property, including, without limitation, debris removal and
5 work to protect or restore public services or public infrastructure.
6 “(3) The Governor may activate the program if:
7 “(a) The Governor determines that an emergency has occurred or
8 is imminent and finds that assistance from the state is warranted; and
9 “(b) The department recommends that the program be activated.
10 “(4) The Governor shall inactivate the program when the Governor
11 finds that assistance from the state is no longer warranted.
12 “(5) While the program is active, the department may issue grants
13 to qualified recipients pursuant to requests from counties or tribal
14 entities. A request on behalf of a city may be made by the county in
15 which a geographic majority of the city lies. Requests must be in
16 writing and must include the following information:
17 “(a) Confirmation that the requester has taken appropriate action
18 under the local emergency plan;
19 “(b) An estimate of the amount and severity of damages and losses
20 and a description of the impact of the emergency on the public and
21 private sectors;
22 “(c) A description of the nature and amount of local resources
23 which have been or will be committed to alleviate the results of the
24 emergency;
25 “(d) A preliminary estimate of the types and amount of supple-
26 mentary state emergency assistance needed; and
27 “(e) A certification by the requester that the obligations and ex-
28 penditures for the current emergency will comply with all applicable
29 cost sharing requirements agreed between the department and the re-
30 quester.
HB 4121-A3 2/24/26
Proposed Amendments to A-Eng. HB 4121 Page 11

1 “(6) The department may adopt rules to administer and implement
2 the provisions of this section, including rules governing eligibility re-
3 quirements, the form and manner of requests and evaluation of re-
4 quests by the department.
5 “(7) As used in this section, ‘qualified recipient’ means:
6 “(a) A state agency;
7 “(b) A local government;
8 “(c) A federally recognized Indian tribe in Oregon;
9 “(d) A school district or education service district; and
10 “(e) A nonprofit organization that provides critical services or es-
11 sential social services, such as a hospital, long term care facility,
12 school, community center, food assistance program or shelter.
13 “SECTION 17. The Oregon Public Assistance Grant Program Ac-
14 count is established in the State Treasury, separate and distinct from
15 the General Fund. Interest earned by the account must be credited to
16 the account. The account consists of moneys appropriated, allocated,
17 deposited or transferred to the account by the Legislative Assembly
18 or otherwise and interest earned on moneys in the account. The
19 moneys in the account are continuously appropriated to the Oregon
20 Department of Emergency Management to carry out the Oregon Pub-
21 lic Assistance Grant Program described in section 16 of this 2026 Act.
22 The department shall ensure that no more than 10 percent of the
23 moneys in the account are used to pay costs of coordination and dis-
24 tribution of assistance under the program.
25 “SECTION 18. (1) The Department of Human Services shall estab-
26 lish and administer an individual grant program, to be known as the
27 Oregon Individual Assistance Grant Program, to issue grants to ad-
28 dress critical emergency-related needs of qualified individuals, subject
29 to available funding.
30 “(2) The Governor may activate the program if:
HB 4121-A3 2/24/26
Proposed Amendments to A-Eng. HB 4121 Page 12

1 “(a) The Oregon Department of Emergency Management recom-
2 mends that the program be activated, the Governor determines that
3 an emergency has occurred or is imminent and the Governor finds
4 that assistance from the state is warranted; or
5 “(b) The Governor has declared an emergency under ORS 401.165.
6 “(3) The Governor shall inactivate the program when the Governor
7 finds that assistance from the state is no longer warranted.
8 “(4) While the program is active, the Department of Human Ser-
9 vices may issue grants pursuant to requests from counties or tribal
10 entities. A request on behalf of a city may be made by the county in
11 which a geographic majority of the city lies. Requests must be in
12 writing and must include the following information:
13 “(a) Confirmation that the requester has taken appropriate action
14 under the local emergency plan;
15 “(b) An estimate of the amount and severity of damages and losses
16 and a description of the impact of the emergency on individuals and
17 households;
18 “(c) A description of the nature and amount of local resources
19 which have been or will be committed to alleviate the results of the
20 emergency; and
21 “(d) A preliminary estimate of the types and amount of supple-
22 mentary state emergency assistance needed.
23 “(5) Grants under the program may be used only to pay for:
24 “(a) The provision of services to qualified individuals for critical
25 emergency-related needs, which may include, without limitation:
26 “(A) Temporary rental assistance;
27 “(B) Hazard mitigation assistance;
28 “(C) Repair or replacement of owner-occupied homes that serve as
29 a primary residence, including repair or replacement of privately
30 owned access routes;
HB 4121-A3 2/24/26
Proposed Amendments to A-Eng. HB 4121 Page 13

1 “(D) Assistance with immediate needs;
2 “(E) Essential personal property assistance;
3 “(F) Assistance with other serious needs that are not covered by
4 insurance; and
5 “(G) Other critical emergency recovery services as approved by the
6 Oregon Department of Emergency Management; and
7 “(b) Agreements with local governments, tribal entities or disaster
8 recovery organizations for the delivery of services described in para-
9 graph (a) of this subsection, including payments for staffing or other
10 administrative needs.
11 “(6) Assistance to individuals may be in the form of direct financial
12 assistance or payments to another entity on behalf of individuals.
13 “(7) The Department of Human Services, in consultation with the
14 Oregon Department of Emergency Management, may adopt rules to
15 administer and implement the provisions of this section.
16 “(8) The Oregon Department of Emergency Management, in con-
17 sultation with the Department of Human Services, shall update the
18 statewide emergency management plan prepared under ORS 401.052 to
19 incorporate the Oregon Individual Assistance Grant Program into
20 statewide disaster response and recovery planning. The plan must in-
21 clude, without limitation, provisions for equitable distribution of as-
22 sistance, coordination with local governments and community-based
23 organizations, and integration with federal recovery programs when
24 applicable.
25 “(9) As used in this section:
26 “(a) ‘Hazard mitigation’ means actions taken to reduce impacts of
27 future emergencies.
28 “(b) ‘Immediate need’ means:
29 “(A) A life-saving or life-sustaining item or activity that is essential
30 to prevent, mitigate or overcome an adverse condition caused by an
HB 4121-A3 2/24/26
Proposed Amendments to A-Eng. HB 4121 Page 14

1 emergency; and
2 “(B) Other equipment that is essential for daily household needs.
3 “(c) ‘Qualified individual’ means:
4 “(A) An individual who is displaced by an emergency from the
5 individual’s primary residence;
6 “(B) An individual whose primary residence is rendered
7 uninhabitable by an emergency; or
8 “(C) An individual with a disability whose primary residence is
9 rendered inaccessible or uninhabitable to the individual as a result of
10 damage caused by an emergency.
11 “SECTION 19. The Oregon Individual Assistance Grant Program
12 Account is established in the State Treasury, separate and distinct
13 from the General Fund. Interest earned by the account must be cred-
14 ited to the account. The account consists of moneys appropriated, al-
15 located, deposited or transferred to the account by the Legislative
16 Assembly or otherwise and interest earned on moneys in the account.
17 The moneys in the account are continuously appropriated to the
18 Oregon Department of Emergency Management. The department may
19 make moneys in the account available to the Department of Human
20 Services to carry out the Oregon Individual Assistance Grant Program
21 described in section 18 of this 2026 Act.
22
